#T_RL=webanno.custom.Coref|type|BT_webanno.custom.Referent
#Text=( ( WSS ) )
#Text=Will you support him during the November election or somebody else ?
#Text=Wolfe : Well , if he says he 'll support me if I win , then I might reciprocate .
#Text=I think we 'll just have to look at it and see how far and wide he appeals .
#Text=But I certainly would expect to .
#Text=I certainly would like to .
#Text=Sure .
#Text=( ( WSS ) ) But if it was a choice between him and [ Mitt ] Romney , who would you favor ?
#Text=Wolfe : Well if it came down to those two , I would just have to see where they are .

#Text=I expect to support the president , but to me , there 's not a lot of difference between him and Romney on the economy and there 's not that much difference between him and Romney on foreign affairs .
#Text=There 's not that much difference between him and Romney on civil liberties .
#Text=The differences are a lot narrower than people think and they mostly arise in areas again of identity politics .
#Text=It seems to me like Romney is wanting to repeal abortion rights .
#Text=He even wants to cut back on birth control .
#Text=It seems to me that he wants us to get involved in even more wars .
#Text=He wants to actually to increase military spending by 20 percent .
#Text=His foreign policy advisers are interventionists .
#Text=They 're neo-cons .
#Text=They 're dangerous people , who do n't even see Iraq as a mistake , who would like to get us involved even more deeply in areas like Syria and North Korea , places like that .
#Text=Romney alarms me a lot more than Obama does in that area .
#Text=I think Romney would probably give too many tax cuts to the well-to-do , the ones that are already very wealthy .
#Text=I think that Obama would at least put an end to that .
#Text=I do n't think he pushed quite that hard for a tax increase , but I do n't think he 'd even fight for tax reductions either .
#Text=Corporate taxes as a proportion of GDP has decreased since the 1950s .
#Text=Image : Guest2625 .
#Text=Corporations and things are very powerful .

#Text=The one message Obama has failed to get out is that the corporate tax rate in this country may be 35 percent on paper , see the effective tax rate that these corporations pay , if you just look at the average of what the Fortune 500 pay it 's only 16 percent .
#Text=So that 's the way it really works because you got lobbyists in Washington that write the accounting rules , that write the tax rules and everything , so the 35 percent thing is just a mirage .

#Text=All it 's done is whip up ... to make people think we 're non-competitive because we have a higher rater on paper than people like Japan or Germany or maybe some like Mexico or some third world country .
#Text=Right now if you look at the corporate tax collective , they make up the lowest percentage of GDP than ever .
#Text=I think we 've paid $ 200 billion on a $ 15 trillion economy .
#Text=So you 're talking about maybe one and a half percent .
#Text=Under [ President Dwight ]
#Text=Eisenhower , the federal tax was collected and corporations made up about 25 percent of the budget receipts .
#Text=Now they make up maybe nine percent , and corporations now are 15 times as big and powerful as they were under Eisenhower .
#Text=So the corporation is ... they want to make people look like they 're victims .
#Text=I mean it 's just pathetic .
